rtaining book, leading computer scientist Brian Kernighan teaches anyone—even diehard math-phobes—how to demystify the numbers that assault us every day.With examples drawn from a rich variety of sources, including journalism, advertising, and politics, Kernighan demonstrates how numbers can mislead and misrepresent. In chapters covering big numbers, units, dimensions, and more, he lays bare everything from deceptive graphs to speciously precise numbers. And he shows how anyone—using a few basic ideas and lots of shortcuts—can easily learn to recognize common mistakes, determine whether numbers are credible, and make their own sensible estimates when needed.Giving you the simple tools you need to avoid being fooled by dubious numbers, Millions, Billions, Zillions is an essential survival guide for a world drowning in big—and often bad—data.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aData mining. 0aNumbers, Complex. 7aMATHEMATICS / Counting & Numeration.2bisacsh  aA picture is worth a thousand words.  aAARP.  aAmerican Medical Association.  aApproximation.  aArithmetic mean.  aArithmetic.  aAssociated Press.  aBaby boomers.  aBack-of-the-envelope calculation.  aBarrel (unit).  aBirth rate.  aBlogger (service).  aBody surface area.  aBreast cancer.  aCalculation.  aCelsius.  aCentenarian.  aComputation.  aConsumer Reports.  aCorporate tax.  aCorrelation does not imply causation.  aDaniel Kahneman.  aDarrell Huff.  aDilbert.  aDot-com bubble.  aEconomics.  aEdward Tufte.  aError.  aEstimation.  aExabyte.  aExponential growth.  aFLOPS.  aFactoid.  aFermi problem.  aGigabyte.  aHalf Gone.  aHeadline.  aHectare.  aHome computer.  aHow to Lie with Statistics.  aHulu.  aIdentity theft.  aInception.  aInflation.  aInnumeracy (book).  aJeff Bezo